      "description": "The market's 'fear gauge': expected volatility of the S&P 500 over the next 30 days, implied by option prices. Rough guide: under ~15 = calm, 20-30 = nervous, above 30 = fear/panic - historically when bargains appear."
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "type": "table",
      "title": "CEF universe - now (sorted by z-score: most anomalously cheap first)",
      "description": "One row per CEF from gold.cef_snapshot. Premium/discount sign convention: negative = discount (buy zone), positive = premium. NAV quality: estimado = normal intraday state (yesterday's NAV); rancio = NAV older than 4 days, scraper likely failing. | Z-SCORE, in plain words: how unusual today's premium/discount is versus that fund's OWN last year, in standard deviations. 0 = its normal level; -2 = unusually cheap (roughly the cheapest ~2% of days); +2 = unusually expensive. Big negative z-score with enough observations (Obs 1y) = the anomaly worth investigating.",
      "gridPos": {
        "h": 12,
        "w": 24,
        "x": 0,
        "y": 5
      },
      "datasource": {
        "type": "grafana-postgresql-datasource",
        "uid": "neon-sentinel"
      },
      "targets": [
        {
          "refId": "A",
          "format": "table",
          "rawSql": "SELECT ticker AS \"CEF\", price AS \"Price\", nav AS \"NAV\", nav_date AS \"NAV date\", nav_quality AS \"NAV quality\", round(premium_discount * 100, 2) AS \"Prem/Disc %\", estado AS \"Status\", round(zscore::numeric, 2) AS \"Z-score\", n_obs AS \"Obs (1y)\", zscore_date AS \"Z-score date\" FROM gold.cef_snapshot ORDER BY zscore ASC NULLS LAST"
        }
      ],
      "options": {
        "sortBy": []
      },
      "fieldConfig": {
        "defaults": {
          "custom": {
            "align": "auto",
            "cellOptions": {
              "type": "auto"
            }
          }
        },
        "overrides": [
